			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2023</a> paper:</span><br><i>Enabling Blended Modelling of Timing and Variability in EAST-ADL</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MuhammadWaseemAnwar.html">Muhammad Waseem Anwar</a>, <a href="../profile/FedericoCiccozzi.html">Federico Ciccozzi</a>, <a href="../profile/AlessioBucaioni.html">Alessio Bucaioni</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3623476.3623518">10.1145/3623476.3623518</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The work extends and supports the EAST-ADL domain-specific modelling language with blended modelling facilities.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagL">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> A major concern is variability modelling, which aligns with product-line style variability management.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6f.html"><span class="tagL">T6F: CPS/IoT/DT</span></a><ul><li> EAST-ADL targets automotive embedded systems, placing the contribution in a CPS/IoT domain context.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> Blended modelling involves multiple concrete syntaxes (often including graphical views), making visual interaction a secondary concern.
</li></ul></li></ul>
